<h2>
    What are git aliases?
</h2>
<p>
    Git aliases are useful shortcuts for long 
    terminal commands. 
    It makes using git faster and easier. 
</p>

<p>
    To create custom aliases, use the git <code>config</code> command. 
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-shell">git config --global alias.co checkout
git config --global alias.br branch
git config --global alias.ci commit
git config --global alias.st status</code></pre>

<p>
    The name with the alias is all that has to be called. In this 
    example, co is checkout, br is branch, ci is commit and st is status. 
    Feel free to create new aliases: that's what they were made for.  
</p>

<h2>
    Some useful examples
</h2>

<p>
    A good example is <code class="lang-shell">git config --global alias.unstage 'reset HEAD --'</code>, which will 
    create a new unstage command. To use it, just type <code class="lang-shell">git unstage </code> and the filename 
    to unstage a file. 
</p>
<p>
    Now these two statements are equivalent:
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-shell">git unstage fileX
git reset HEAD -- fileX
</code></pre>

<p>
    Another good alias to have is <code>last</code>, which displays the last commit 
    using <code class="lang-shell">git config --global alias.last 'log -1 HEAD'</code>. This 
    is useful for quickly grabbing the latest commit. 
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-shell">git config --global alias.last 'log -1 HEAD'
git last
:'commit 0745d369ae306d0ecdf4ec4fbd7a710ca271baa4 (HEAD -> main, origin/main, origin/HEAD)
Author: Alec Sears &lt;76724804+searsam1@users.noreply.github.com&gt;
Date:   Mon Dec 19 04:42:10 2022 -0700

    add tests
    
    add 100 tests that compare fact and math.factorial
    '

</code></pre>

<h2>
    External Commands
</h2>
<p>
    It is possible to run commands outside of git
    by adding <code>!</code> in front of the command. 
    For example:  
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-shell">git config --global alias.visual '!gitk'</code></pre>
